Subsequently, the developed sensor based on B-CDs@SiO2/CdTe MIP was applied to sensing DA. As illustrated in Fig. 4B and C, the fluorescence intensity at 610 nm of designed sensor reveals regular quenching and the fluorescence intensity ratio (F610/F430) gradually decreases with the addition of DA in the concentration range of 0–5 μM. Surprisingly, a good linear relationship between the logarithm of F610/F430 and the level of DA is obtained within the range from 0.03 μM to 1 μM with a correlation coefficient (R

                           2
                        ) of 0.998 (Fig. 4D). The linear equation can be fitted as: ln(F610/F430) = −0.793[DA] + 0.602, and the limit of detection (LOD) is determined to be as low as 0.018 μM (S/N = 3). Compared with B-CDs@SiO2/CdTe MIP, the B-CDs@SiO2/CdTe NIP displays lower sensitivity and narrower linear range to DA. This phenomenon is owing to the absence of specific recognition sites in the B-CDs@SiO2/CdTe NIP-based ratiometric fluorescence sensor and the DA cannot invade the NIP inner to interact with CdTe QDs (Fig. S12). Apparently, our proposed method is comparable to these previous strategies in terms of detection range and LOD (Table.S2). More importantly, our method additionally exhibits the superiorities of simple operation, low cost, and short detection time. Additionally, our designed sensor with good stability can maintain almost constant sensing performance within 15 days (Fig. S13). More attractively, the removal-rebinding cycle experiments demonstrate that the developed sensor can still measure DA accurately during three cycles, illustrating that the sensor has good reusability (Fig. S14). Such advantages make the method have significant prospects in practical applications.
